ladders.explanation:
The brute force approach solves the problem by directly implementing the definition: for each element at index i, we need to compute the product of all elements except nums[i]. This is achieved using two nested loops. The outer loop iterates through each index i from 0 to n-1. For each i, we initialize a product variable to 1 (the multiplicative identity). The inner loop iterates through all indices j from 0 to n-1. If j ≠ i, we multiply the current product by nums[j]. After the inner loop completes, we store this product in the result array at position i. The intuition is straightforward: we're manually computing the required product for each position by excluding the current element through conditional checking. This approach is conceptually simple but computationally expensive. Time complexity is O(n²) because for each of n elements, we perform up to n multiplications (n-1 actually, but O(n) per element). Space complexity is O(1) excluding the output array, as we only use a few variables. This connects directly to the problem statement - it's the most literal translation of requirements to code. Common mistakes include forgetting to reset product to 1 for each i, incorrectly handling the j ≠ i condition (using j == i instead), or not handling edge cases like single-element arrays. The real code pattern involves nested for loops with a conditional multiplication.

Pseudocode:
function productExceptSelf(nums):
    n = length(nums)
    result = array of size n
    for i from 0 to n-1:
        product = 1
        for j from 0 to n-1:
            if j != i:
                product = product * nums[j]
        result[i] = product
    return result

This sub-routine is the heart of the brute force approach. For a given index i in an array nums, we need to compute the product of all elements except nums[i]. The intuition is simple: iterate through the entire array, multiply all elements together, but skip the element at position i. We initialize product to 1 (since 1 multiplied by any number gives that number). Then we loop through all indices j from 0 to n-1. For each j, we check if j ≠ i. If true, we multiply product by nums[j]. If false (j = i), we skip that element. After the loop, product contains the desired result. This demonstrates the core multiplication logic while handling the exclusion requirement. Time complexity is O(n) for a single index since we examine each element once. Space complexity is O(1) as we only use the product variable. This feeds into the full problem (L0) by being the inner loop computation - the full problem calls this routine for each index i. Common mistakes include forgetting to initialize product to 1, incorrectly implementing the skip condition (using j == i instead of j != i), or not handling the case when all other elements multiply to zero. The real code pattern is a for loop with conditional multiplication.

